<div id="review_2030876581" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2030876581" />
    <a title="Ella May" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/66323536-ella-may"><img alt="Ella May" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2030876581?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ella May" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ella May" href="/user/show/66323536-ella-may">Ella May</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2030876581" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1442577962334930226">J.P. Willson describes his journey into addiction and out the other side into his current path. In his case, the addiction was alcohol, but this book is relatable to all sorts of addictions, I believe. The author mentions several times that his journey is a personal one. He is not offering this memoir as a cure-all prescription. He says in the introduction that he wrote this book to help himself to heal, and also to help others on their own journeys. <br/>I read this book from the viewpoint of a pers</span>
  <span id="freeText1442577962334930226" style="display:none">J.P. Willson describes his journey into addiction and out the other side into his current path. In his case, the addiction was alcohol, but this book is relatable to all sorts of addictions, I believe. The author mentions several times that his journey is a personal one. He is not offering this memoir as a cure-all prescription. He says in the introduction that he wrote this book to help himself to heal, and also to help others on their own journeys. <br />I read this book from the viewpoint of a person who has someone close to them suffering from addiction, and I found it helpful to glean at least a little part of what the struggle is like for the addict attempting to remake his or her life without depending on an addictive substance. I therefore recommend "Through the Mind's Eye" to friends and family members on the outside looking in, as much as I would recommend it to those who are aware of their addiction and are seeking a way out, or at least a way forward. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1442577962334930226" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


